<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-345-020  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 345 020.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 12 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Michigan Bell to build fiber optic rings. (Michigan Bell TelephoneCo.)(around Detroit and Grand Rapids, Michigan)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Michigan Bell Telephone Co. (planning).andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsPlanningFiber opticsMichiganNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MICHIGAN BELL TO BUILD FIBER OPTIC RINGS DETROIT, MICHIGAN, U.S.A., 1990 APR9 (NB) -- Michigan Bell has announced it will ring downtown Detroit and GrandRapids, MI with fiber optic cable in an attempt to forestall attempts byothers to do the same thing.andP;  The business of bypassing Bell company serviceswith fiber optic cable has boomed in recent years.andM;&quot;The rings will expand customer access to the latest system technology andoffer increased capacity and transmission reliability,&quot; said Michigan BellPresident Kenneth E. Millard, offering shorter installation time for newservices, greater ability to monitor service quality and increasedtransmission capacity.andP;  Construction will begin in May, with servicebeginning in late 1990.andP;  Each ring will connect customers in downtownbuildings with two separate Michigan Bell call-processing offices, creatingadditional paths on which information can travel.andP;  The Detroit ring will run6 miles from linking Michigan Bell's call-processing offices at 1365 Cass and1014 E. Jefferson.andP;  They're the first phase of a year $50 million program toprovide new &quot;self-correcting&quot; transmission routes for calls.andP;  The companyplans to build fiber rings in all its major markets.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900410/Press Contact: Phil Jones, Michigan Bell313-963-2398)</TEXT></DOC>